  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These laws are not directly enforceable in national courts, but they provide a framework for countries to adopt their own domestic laws and regulations to criminalize and prevent money laundering.  They also promote international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting these crimes.\n\nHere's a breakdown of some key international instruments:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was a landmark agreement that recognized drug trafficking as a transnational criminal activity and urged states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking. It established the concept of money laundering as a specific offense.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention extended the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the proceeds of a wider range of serious crimes, including organized crime, corruption, and terrorism. It also emphasizes international cooperation in asset forfeiture and extradition.\n\n*   **The International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** While primarily focused on terrorism financing, this convention also addresses the laundering of funds used for terrorist activities.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** The FATF is an inter-governmental body that develops and promotes policies to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Its 40 Recommendations (and 9 Special Recommendations on Terrorist Financing) are the international standard for combating these crimes. While not a treaty, these recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world and are considered best practices. The FATF also conducts evaluations of member countries' compliance with these standards.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and Revised Convention (2005):** These conventions aim to harmonize and improve national laws relating to money laundering and asset forfeiture among European states.\n\n**Key Provisions and Principles in these Laws:**\n\n*   **Criminalization:**  Requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from a wide range of predicate offenses.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence:**  Requires financial institutions and other designated businesses to identify their customers, verify their identities, and conduct ongoing monitoring of their accounts and transactions.\n*   **Record Keeping:**  Requires financial institutions to maintain records of transactions for a specified period.\n*   **Reporting Suspicious Transactions:**  Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to a designated financial intelligence unit (FIU).\n*   **International Cooperation:**  Encourages states to cooperate with each other in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses, including sharing information, providing mutual legal assistance, and extraditing offenders.\n*   **Asset Forfeiture:**  Allows for the confiscation of assets derived from or used to commit money laundering.\n\n**Enforcement:**\n\nThe enforcement of these international laws primarily relies on individual countries incorporating these principles into their domestic laws and regulations.  International cooperation through mechanisms like mutual legal assistance treaties (MLATs) and extradition agreements is critical for investigating and prosecuting cross-border money laundering cases.\n\nIn summary, while there isn't a single, universally enforceable \"international law\" against money laundering, a comprehensive framework of international conventions, standards, and recommendations exists. This framework guides countries in developing and implementing their own laws and fostering international cooperation to combat this global problem.\n",
